proof.p:
A square matrix either has an inverse ( is invertible) or it doesn't ( is singular). We would like to know that in the invertible case, there can be only one inverse. So suppose that A is a square matrix, and that B is an inverse for A. Then, by definition we have both BA=I and AB=I (see ). What if we had another inverse for A? Suppose C was also an inverse for A, so that both CA=I and AC=I were true. Here, all of A,B,C,I are square of the same size. But then,
C \amp= CI \amp \amp\text{(i)} \amp= C(AB) \amp \amp\text{(ii)} \amp= (CA)B \amp \amp\text{(iii)} \amp= IB \amp \amp\text{(iv)} \amp= B \amp \amp\text{(v)},
with justifications
Rule of ;
B is an inverse for A;
Rule of ;
C is an inverse for A; and
Rule of .
So C and B must actually be the same inverse for A. Since we can apply the same reasoning to any inverse for A, there can only be one inverse for A.

We have a square matrix A = MN and would like to find an inverse B for it. Let's try B = \inv{N}\inv{M}:
BA \amp= (\inv{N}\inv{M})(MN) \amp AB \amp= (MN)(\inv{N}\inv{M})
\amp = \inv{N}(\inv{M}M)N \amp \amp = M(N\inv{N})\inv{M}
\amp = \inv{N}IN \amp \amp = MI\inv{M}
\amp = I, \amp \amp = I,
where in the first steps we have applied Rule of .

